### Importing all samples to understand the expression profile
Controls: F07007, F014932, F012262-4  
DMD patients without TEA: C023903, C026484, F012161-1  
DMD patients with TEA: C026023, F012161-4, C026786

Related individuals: F012161-1 and F012161-4 are monozygotic twins

Samples MRP1 to 9 are NSCs, while MRP10 to 18 are neurons

- In this step, all samples will be analyzed separately to identify possible outliers and low-quality samples.

#### Pre-processing

```{r warning = TRUE}
# build the samples manually to change everything easily
setwd("/PROJECT_DIR/RSEM_quant/")
samples <- data.frame(sample = as.factor(gsub("(.+?)(\\_.*)", "\\1", list.files(pattern = ".genes.results"))),
                      condition=c("control","control","control","control",rep("patient",6),rep("control",2),rep("patient",6)),
                      mut_type=c(rep("none",4),"duplication","deletion","deletion","indel","deletion","snv",
                                 "none","none","duplication","deletion","deletion","indel","deletion","snv"),
                      TEA=c(rep("no",7),rep("yes",3),rep("no",5),rep("yes",3)),
                      individual=c("F07007","F07007","F014932","F012262-4","C023903","C026484","F012161-1","C026023","F012161-4",
                                   "C026786","F014932","F012262-4","C023903","C026484","F012161-1","C026023","F012161-4","C026786"),
                      new_name=c("C1","C1","C2","C3","P1","P2","P3","P4","P5","P6","C2","C3","P1","P2","P3","P4","P5","P6"),
                      age=c(27,27,25,9,16,20,20,15,20,14,25,9,16,20,20,15,20,14),
                      cell_type=c("NSC",rep("neuron",9),rep("NSC",8)))
samples$data <- paste(samples$new_name,samples$cell_type,sep="_")
#samples$group <- paste(samples$DMD_condition,samples$TEA,sep="")

write.table(samples, file = "/PROJECT_DIR/metadata.txt", sep = "\t", quote = FALSE)

files <- list.files(pattern = ".genes.results")
names(files) <- samples$sample
all(file.exists(files))

# import quantified reads (counts)
txi = tximport(files, type = "rsem", txIn = FALSE, txOut = FALSE)
txi$length[txi$length == 0] = 0.01

# create deseq2 object with the information about the samples
dds <- DESeqDataSetFromTximport(txi, colData = samples, design = ~condition)

#check if samples have been correctly assigned to metadata
pt <- as.data.frame(dds@colData)
paged_table(pt)

# In some experiments, it may not be appropriate to assume that a minority of features (genes) are affected greatly by the condition, such that the standard median-ratio method for estimating the size factors will not provide correct inference (the log fold changes for features that were truly un-changing will not centered on zero)
#you can provide control genes that you don't expect to change expression in order to better estimate 
#dds <- estimateSizeFactors(dds, controlGenes=ctrlGenes)
#dds <- DESeq(dds)

# While it is not necessary to pre-filter low count genes before running the DESeq2 functions, there are two reasons which make pre-filtering useful: by removing rows in which there are very few reads, we reduce the memory size of the dds data object, and we increase the speed of count modeling within DESeq2. It can also improve visualizations, as features with no information for differential expression are not plotted in dispersion plots or MA-plots.
smallestGroupSize <- 3
keep <- rowSums(counts(dds) >= 20) >= smallestGroupSize
dds <- dds[keep,]
dds <- DESeq(dds)

counts_table <- counts(dds, normalized = TRUE) ### this is the correct normalization to use if testing for differential expression using limma, it divides counts by the sizeFactor which relates to the library depth
write.table(counts_table, file = "/PROJECT_DIR/RSEM_quant/counts_table.txt", sep = "\t", quote = FALSE)
```


